observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Instruct the Municipal Engineer to carry out planning and detailed engineering activities properly and judiciously, ensuring that project site viability and other potential issues are thoroughly addressed during the feasibility or preliminary engineering stages before project implementation;


Direct the Municipal Engineer to conduct a comprehensive review and evaluation of the POWs to ensure that project designs and estimates are accurately prepared, covering all project phases adequately to minimize the issuance of VOs that could potentially increase project costs, cause delays in project completion or result in the deletion of significant work items that may compromise the integrity and usefulness of the structure;

Direct the Municipal Engineer to submit justifications on the adjustments made to the quantities and cost per unit of work items, which consequently, resulted in the non-adherence of the 10% threshold under Section 1, Annex E of the same Act; and

Impose appropriate sanctions on the designer, consultant, or official responsible for the original detailed engineering design, which failed to consider the VO beyond ten percent.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:

The BAC to ensure that all PPAs including those funded from Continuing Appropriations and DRRMF-STF are included in the APP;


The BAC to strictly follow the time schedule of procurement activities identified in the APP;


The Municipal Engineer to see to it that POWs already support the identified PPAs during the preparation of the budget taken consideration in-depth planning as to prevent frequent changes of POWs; and

The department heads of implementing office such as Municipal Engineer, LDRRM Officer, GAD Focal Person and MPPC to see to it that PPAs are specifically identified in the fund’s plan and budget.

We recommended that the LCE substantially comply with the Circular by:

Enjoining all the concerned/ responsible offices, first and foremost, to properly and adequately plan the retrieval of records, conduct of inventory and recording of LRNs;

Directing the Inventory Committee to properly conduct physical inventory of LRNs by segregating and recognizing the cost of each component of the local roads, if possible;

Instructing the Municipal Engineer to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer-Designate on the retrieval of the documents related to LRNs constructed prior to CY 2009; and

The Property Officer-Designate and the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the pertinent records and reports.

We recommended that CDRRMO:
Ensure the timely implementation of the PPAs outlined in the Catch-up Plan;
Conduct a thorough assessment and evaluation of previously implemented PPAs to determine their effectiveness and relevance before initiating similar initiatives to prevent redundancy, optimize resource allocation to ensure that future programs address remaining gaps or evolving needs rather than duplicating past efforts;
Meticulously plan the budget for every PPAs to prevent price related issues, ensuring that cost estimates are accurate, aligned with market rates, and within the available financial resources; and
Consider the hiring of additional personnel to address staffing concerns, ensuring sufficient personnel to effectively carry out essential tasks and responsibilities.

The Audit Team recommended that the LCE:
instruct the Inventory Committee to prioritize the conduct of a thorough and complete physical inventory and reconcile the results thereon with the accounting records to ascertain the accuracy, completeness and existence of the reported PPE in the financial statement;
instruct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, to facilitate the preparation of Local Road Inventory and Road Map and aids in the conduct of physical inventory on road network projects;
instruct the Municipal Accountant and Inventory Committee to reclassify the properties costing below P50,000.00 to semi-expendable properties; and
instruct the Property Officer, the Head of Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to take advantage of the intentions of COA Circular 2020-06 dated January 31, 2020 by adhering with the guidelines and procedures set forth under the Circular in the  conduct  of physical count of properties; recognition of PPE items found at station; disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items; and for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, to reflect more reliable and accurate balances of PPE accounts in the FS, hence to convey precise information useful in decision making and accountability for these properties.

The Audit Team recommended that Management:
Judiciously and meticulously plan the PPAs to be included in the APP where all the required details such as:
the Name of Procurement Project;
Procurement Management Office (PMO)/end-user/implementing unit;
Method of Procurement;
Schedule of identified procurement activities as reflected in the APP form approved by the GPPB;
Source of funds;
Indicative ABC;
and other relevant descriptions of the project, if applicable.
Hence to have an accurate basis in the execution of the PAPs and in the conduct of proper procurement process in accordance with the provisions of RA No. 9184;
Enforce a centralized system on the procurement of supplies, materials and equipment for proper control on the acquisition and issuances thereof wherein the GSO will determine the items to be procured on a quarterly basis based on the Consolidated APP of the Municipality and require the BAC to conduct a public bidding for items not available in the PS-DBM, hence to avail more advantageous prices and to adhere with the policy of transparency, accountability, equity, efficiency, and economy in the procurement process;
Require the Office of the GSO/Municipal Treasurer to ensure that PRs, POs, AIRs and other supporting documents pertaining to the procurement of supplies, materials and equipment are serially numbered, dated, and duly filled-out; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to record the purchases of supplies and materials to be carried in stock as inventory regardless of whether or not they are consumed within the accounting period following the perpetual inventory method.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Agriculturist to undertake the following actions:
Immediately submit to the Municipal Accountant all necessary reports and supporting documents to serve as the basis for the accurate recognition, valuation, and recording of Biological Assets, particularly for the proper accounting of any gains or losses arising from changes in asset value;
Furnish the Municipal Accountant with copies of the executed MOAs and regular monitoring reports pertaining to the distributed breeding stocks, to ensure adequate legal and documentary support for the program;
Initiate the tagging of distributed breeding stocks with appropriate property identification markers to facilitate ease of recognition during physical inventory and monitoring activities;
Immediately report any incidents of mortality or loss of breeding stocks and promptly initiate the process for requesting relief from accountability in accordance with applicable guidelines and regulations; and
Formulate and institutionalize a written policy or set of procedures governing the proper implementation and management of the LGU’s breeding program, in coordination with other relevant offices and personnel, to ensure consistency, accountability, and effective oversight.
We further recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to include a comprehensive narrative description and appropriate disclosures regarding Biological Assets in the Notes to the Financial Statements. This should incorporate relevant data and insights from the reports of the Municipal Agriculturist to ensure that users and stakeholders are equipped with sufficient information to make well-informed decisions.
The Municipal Agriculturist is in the process of locating supporting documents—such as goat death certificates and photographs—for the reported fatalities. She has also assured that a comprehensive report on the status of breeding stocks, including all relevant attachments, will be submitted in due course. Additionally, the Municipal Accountant signified compliance with the audit recommendations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
BAC to:
Ensure the inclusion of all procurement items in the APP, regardless of the mode of procurement, to provide a comprehensive basis for validation and monitoring and that total estimated cost of all projects reflected therein must not exceed the approved budget appropriations for the fiscal year – upholding budget credibility and preventing unauthorized procurements;
Submit the final APP to the GPPB within the prescribed timeline, and ensure that receipt is duly acknowledged and the same must be uploaded to the GPPB website to comply with transparency requirements and promote public access to procurement information;
Diligently and completely fill out essential sections of the bidding documents, particularly the PBDs, SCC and Technical Specifications in order to ensure clear and unambiguous instructions to bidders, reduce the risk of bid disqualification or misinterpretation, and promote fair and competitive procurement tailored to the PE’s specific needs;
Strictly adhere to prescribed posting periods for procurement activities in order to provide adequate notice to prospective bidders and help prevent procedural irregularities; and
Ensure that all bidding documents are duly signed, especially by the BAC Chairperson and other authorized officials, to establish authenticity, completeness, and validity and to reduce legal vulnerabilities and reinforce the integrity of the procurement process – eliminating doubts on the legitimacy and due observance of procurement rules and procedures.
Municipal Engineer to:
Institutionalize a standard mechanism for the preparation of the ABC, incorporating the specific provisions outlined in DPWH DO No. 197, series of 2016;
Provide the Detailed Estimate or DUPA for the CSHP work item, ensuring alignment with the minimum OSHS requirements prescribed by the DOLE; and
Conduct periodic inspections to verify the contractor’s compliance with OSHS standards, and to ensure that each inspection is supported by appropriate documentation, including photographs and field reports.
Management signified their strict compliance with the audit recommendations and assured that the BAC will strictly follow the provisions of the Procurement Law.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to enjoin coordination among the department heads concerned to comply with the requirements of COA Circular No. 2015-008, specifically to require the:
Municipal Engineer to:
Provide the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for every road project, as well as the report on the repair/ maintenance of each local road network; and
Reconcile with the Municipal Accounting Office the reports on the Local Road Network.
Supply Officer/ Inventory Committee to:
Conduct an inventory of the local roads under the Municipality’s jurisdiction with the assistance of the Municipal Engineering Office; and to prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network (RPCLRN);
Maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map; and
Maintain a complete Local Road Network Property Card (LRNPC) for all roads and its components and reconcile the same with the records of the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer;
Municipal Accountant to:
Maintain the LRNLC for each Local Road Components with complete description;
Reconcile the LRNLC with the Local Road Inventory and Road Map of the Supply Office and Report on Local Road Network of the Municipal Engineering Office;
Provide the correct depreciation for each road component and make the necessary adjustment to correct the understatement of Accumulated Depreciation recognized for the Road Network account;
Ensure complete disclosure of the total Road Network System in the Notes to the Financial Statements; and
Make an adjusting entry for the reclassification of the Improvement of Multi-purpose Covered Court from Road Networks account to Other Structures account.

