We recommended that the LCE direct the Human Resource Management Officer – Designate to:

Immediately re-compute, trace and reflect the correct leave credit balances of officials and employees who availed of the monetization for CY 2021, and if necessary, retroactively, of all other officials and employees who availed of the previous years’ monetization;

Ensure that deduction of leave credits from monetization, addition from leave credits earned and the accumulated leave balances are accurately reflected in the individual leave cards;

See to it the previous year’s leave credit balances be correctly forwarded to the current year;

Maintain individual employee leave cards in soft and hard copies, and filed in individual folders for proper referencing and ease in monitoring of leave balances;

Prepare Summary of Leave credit balance of all officials and employees at the end of the year for employees’ information and ready reference;

Determine first the balance of employee’s leave credits before granting/approving application for monetization of leaves; and 

Submit to COA the complete leave cards of the retired/separated employees on CY 2021 for further review and verification of their leave balances as of date of retirement.

We also recommended that the LCE consider filling-up any vacant HR plantilla positions in order to provide the HR Division adequate manpower in the performance of their functions; and

We further recommended that the LCE install, implement and monitor a sound internal control in the recording and processing of leave credits of employees.  Periodic internal audit and review of all employees’ accumulated leave should be conducted prior to approval and payment of their respective monetized leave credits and terminal leave benefits.

24. We recommended and the OIC-LDRRMO agreed to coordinate with the OCD on the preparation and submission of the Municipality’s PSCP pursuant to NDRRMC Memorandum No 33, s. 2018.
25. We further recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
a. To conduct risk assessment;
b. To identify critical processes and functions;
c. To determine scenarios that made disrupt normal operation;
d. To conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
e. To formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed templates and requirements in the PSCP guidebook; and
f. To submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the Local Chief Executive for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

1. Strictly follow the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at the station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items and require the Accountant and Property Officer to reconcile their records based on the results of the actual physical inventory and effect necessary adjustments;
2. Prepare the required PIP to be reviewed and approved by the Head of Agency and submitted to the Audit Team at least 10 calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;
