We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Recognize the expense and income accounts in the Trust Fund book amounting to Ᵽ429,168.00 and Ᵽ12,903,307.62, respectively;



Recognize the Biological Assets under the General Fund totaling Ᵽ3,513,500.00 and provide disclosure in the NFS;



Effect the necessary changes on equity accounts and present it in the Statement of Changes in Net Assets or Equity (SCNAE);



In the ensuing years, recognize appropriate expense or asset account upon incurrence of expenditures and after the utilization of Trust Fund, reduce the corresponding liability account and recognize revenue.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:

Municipal Engineer to furnish GPPA Report, supported with SWA to the Municipal Accountant to serve as the basis for recognition of construction in progress and accounts payable account;



The Municipal Accountant to recognize CIP and Accounts Payable accounts amounting to Ᵽ3,099,936.84.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Direct the BAC to strictly comply with the prescribed period of conducting the pre-bid conferences;




Direct the BAC to comply with the prescribed period of issuance of the NOAs;



BAC Secretariat to ensure that all relevant documents issued to the bidder, particularly the NOA, are duly affixed with the date of receipt of the concerned bidder; and

Instruct the BAC Secretariat to post the NOAs on the PhilGEPS website within the prescribed period.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:

Municipal Treasurer to:

Strictly implement the provisions of the Municipal Revenue Code in order to correct the assessment and collection of business taxes that will accrue to the Municipality;



Conduct regular inspection and verification of financial records of the business establishments to ensure that the correct gross receipts will be declared by the taxpayer;

Set up or institutionalize a standard computation that could have arrive in a more realistic basis of business taxes in the absence of the required audited financial statements or BIR returns or sworn declaration of the gross receipts; and

Maintain periodic review together with concerned officials to ascertain whether collection targets are attained.  Those reasons for the shortfall in collections should be analyzed and alternative methods or procedures be undertaken to avoid the incurrence of shortfall in the future;

Municipal Business and Permits Licensing Officer to:

Refrain from accepting application for the renewal of business permits which are not based on the documentary requirements like the audited financial statements or BIR returns or sworn declaration particularly when the taxpayer submit prior year’s gross receipts in rounded figures;

Require submission of complete documentation of the financial records from taxpayers for the correct assessment of taxes;

Maintain and use an individual ledger or index card for each business establishment in recording their tax payment.

21. Strictly follow the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to have reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability as follows:
a. Strictly follow the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at the station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items and require the Accountant and Property Officer to reconcile their records based on the results of the actual physical inventory and effect necessary adjustments;
b. Adopt the uniform numbering system for property numbers of PPE and require the Property Unit to update the property stickers based on the prescribed format and to include the required information under Section 5.6 and 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
c. Submit the approved PIP to the COA Audit Team within the prescribed period;
d. Conduct the required preliminary activities prior to inventory taking; and
e. Record/document the physical count daily in a standard ICF prescribed in Annex A of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Create clear-cut policies and guidelines to address the issue on the necessity and propriety of hiring Casual/JOs taking into consideration the existing regular employees; 

Limit the hiring of personnel under Casual/Job Order contracts to those extremely necessary and deploy only to offices that actually are in need of their services; 

Require Job Order employees to submit primary personal identification, undergo interview and the HRMO to evaluate the performance of each JO to mitigate the risk of hiring unqualified personnel; and 

Incorporate in the contract the number of man hours, quantity, and duration of the work to be performed by the JO personnel and require them to submit quantified accomplishments reports to support payments of wages.

