Account for the variances noted between the CAD books and RPCPPE;



Record the property, plant and equipment at cost or at revalued amounts;

Verify with the CAO those properties that were recorded in the Lapsing Schedule (LS) but not in the Assessment Roll (AR) and vice versa;

Properly record the property according to its classification, specification and nature of PPE;

Sort the PPE according to its nature and add the cost of the PPE to the specific property only when it is capitalizable and deduct the cost for the portion of the property which was already dropped or demolished;

Make the necessary adjusting entry to correct the beginning balances of the School Buildings category;

Exert extra effort to determine the details of property items without description/breakdown and lumped as beginning balances and all PPEs without details/ breakdown; and

Make the necessary reclassification/correcting entry for the noted misclassified accounts;

The GSD:

Verify with the CAO those properties that were recorded in the RPCPPE but not in the Assessment Roll and vice versa;

Properly record in the RPCPPE the property according to its classification, specification and nature of PPE;

Record the properties in the RPCPPE which were actually seen and counted during the inventory count of PPE. Significant discrepancies noted during the count should be immediately investigated and explained, and reconciled with the CAD;

Reassess the recorded unserviceable properties and take the necessary action for their immediate disposal in accordance with rules on proper disposal of properties;

Maintain Property/Equipment Cards for all PPE to monitor the additions, deductions and any adjustments relative to the PPE;

Indicate in the Property/Equipment Cards the dates of acquisitions of all properties acquired by the City; and

Coordinate with concerned LGU/government agencies regarding the confirmation of ownership or donation of the land not in the name of the City of San Juan; and

The CAO to update the cost of the property of the City in the Assessment Roll for every renovation, improvement, rehabilitation or the deduction/demolition which materially affects the property.

Request the Bureau of Treasury for the immediate remittance of the 20 percent share of the City from the fire code revenues collected by the Bureau of Fire Protection (BFP)-San Juan Fire Station for the period covering CYs 2010-2016 pursuant to RA 9154; 

Require the CTD to coordinate with the BFP for the requirements needed for the release of the same; and regularly check the correctness of the fire code revenues being assessed and collected by  the BFP, especially on the basis of assessment on all the fire code revenues;

Require the BFP-San Juan Fire Station to submit copies of the Monthly Report of Collections and Remittances to the CTD to facilitate monitoring of the 20 percent share of the City from the fire code revenues; and 

Require the CAD to recognize the receivable from the BFP for fair presentation of the financial statements.

The CTD:

Intensify efforts in order to increase the collection efficiency rate on revenues arising from business taxes by launching vigorous tax information campaign;

Determine/verify the amount of gross sales/receipts declared by the taxpayers by conducting regular examination of the books of accounts of all taxpayers; and

Recompute the annual tax levied on the various business establishments according to the schedule of rates provided in the Revenue Code of the City and accordingly make/cause tax credits on those over assessed or collection of under assessed taxes, as the case maybe;

The CAD:

Prepare and maintain detailed SLs for all accounts in accordance with the Revised Chart of Accounts for LGUs to facilitate proper recording and reporting of financial transactions; and

Use the proper classification in the recording of collections based on the source documents and as reported by the CTD to avoid misclassification of accounts;

The Business Permits and Licenses Office:

Require the taxpayers to submit/attach the pertinent documents to support their declaration in the application forms for business permits; and

Revisit the formula used in computing business taxes in the BPLTAS in accordance with the provisions of the San Juan Revenue Code.

Management to require the implementing Office to submit the liquidation documents to the CAD for Fund Utilization Report preparation as soon as the project is finished /implemented;

The CAD:

Coordinate with the source agencies of the fund transfers and facilitate reconciliation of the accounts for the variance noted in audit; 


Return the interest income to the SA or from where the funds came from under the principle that the City is merely a trustee for said fund or provide information/notify the source agencies on the interest earned from the funds transferred to the City for proper accounting of the same in the books of the SA;


Monitor submission of liquidation reports to the source agencies for timely accounting and reporting of the reciprocal accounts both in the books of the City and the source agencies;

Make sure to obtain a copy of Memorandum of Agreement from every source agency that will transfer funds to the City or secure any contract that will prescribe the duties and responsibilities of the City in terms of utilization and liquidation of the fund and proper recording of the transferred funds;

Prepare aging of the fund transfers to monitor if there are inactive accounts. For unspent balances and excess amount of fund transfers, Management should be guided by the provisions of Section 3.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001. Coordinate with the source agencies for the transfer of the unexpended balance to the General Fund of the City, if the disposition thereof is not stipulated in the MOA; and

Abide by the provisions of the aforementioned COA Circulars.

The CTD:

Conduct assessment of the sources of funds in the process of budgeting/planning and determine whether there is indeed idle funds in the General Fund which could be invested in time deposits;

Ensure that planned PPA are first implemented before investing any remaining funds to achieve the primary objective of the City of providing basic services for the benefits of the constituents;

Exert more effort in determining the sources of the Trust Funds invested in time deposits and utilize the same for the specific purpose/s for which they were created/granted; and

Abide by the rules and stop investing trust funds in time deposits.

Management to strictly adhere to the provisions of Republic Act No. 9184 that procurement of infrastructure projects and goods shall be competitive and transparent, and therefore shall adopt public bidding as the general mode of procurement. This will give chance to other interested suppliers to participate and offer prices most advantageous to the government and for the City to implement projects at the least cost and save valuable resources for other projects despite its limited budget;

The Bids and Awards Committee/Secretariat:

Consolidate properly the PPMP of every department into APP to reflect in the latter report the needs of the City for the entire year and in accordance with the format prescribed by DBM for the common-use supplies and materials, non-common-use supplies, materials and equipment which shows the necessary details such as, the individual items, specifications, total quantity, unit cost, procurement methods to be adopted, the time schedule for each procurement activity and the estimated budget;

Use the APP in the determination of the proper mode of procurement to be resorted to that is advantageous to the City, and refrain from purchasing supplies/materials/equipment on a per department basis; 

Require the concerned Department/Office to regularly update the PPMP of the City and accordingly update the APP once every six months to reflect only the actual needs of the City for the remaining period of the year; 

Consider purchasing common-use supplies from the Procurement Service of the DBM or resort only to other alternative modes of procurement, provided that the City will get the most advantageous prevailing price; 

Perform actual canvass from three suppliers of known qualifications in the determination of ABC for all the goods and services to be procured by the City that should be indicated in the PR and Request for Quotations and prepare abstract of canvass or canvass sheets for said canvassing; and

Invite observers from the required sector as provided for by Section 13 of RA 9184 in the procurement of goods, infrastructure projects and consultancy services;

The GSD:

Adopt the price bulletin maintained by the GSD in the GSMS in the generation of PRs, instead of those encoded by every department in the preparation of their respective PPMPs;  

Accomplish the PR properly, more particularly the units of measure, quantity and the description or technical specification of the items;

Request from the CED the plans or drawings with complete specifications of the projects that require materials to be purchased for the repairs and maintenance of City assets;

Take note of the observations in the inspection of deliveries and comply with the requirements of laws, rules and regulations; and

See to it that deliveries are made within the prescribed terms of delivery as specified in the purchase orders and avoid accepting deliveries in tranches for easy monitoring of the goods delivered to prevent advance and/or incomplete delivery;

The City Engineering Department (CED):

Compute the ABC for the infrastructure projects in accordance with law and in DPWH Department Order No. 197 series of 2016 dated October 7, 2016 for the projects to be procured; 

Prepare plans or drawings with complete specifications for the projects that require purchases of goods for repairs and maintenance of City assets; and 

Take note of the observations in the inspection of PPAs and comply with the requirements of laws, rules and regulations relative to the infrastructure projects of the City.

The City Health Office (CHO):

Require the doctor in charge of every BHC/S to regularly conduct inventory of all supplies/medicines and maintain stock cards for proper monitoring;




Store, monitor and record the supplies/medicines provided by the DOH separately from those procured by the City; 

Properly plan the goods to be procured during the year to avoid procurement of supplies/medicines which are not in the PPMP; 

Utilize the structure built in the West Crame Health Center as birthing home; 

Submit immediately copies of the invoice-receipt for all properties received from DOH to the CAD for recording of the donated supplies/medicines/property in the books of accounts; and

Delegate the inspection of the donated supplies/medicines/equipment to the Head of the Health Centers as a form of control over donated items;

The GSD:

Cause the disposal of the unserviceable property items stored in the health center and comply with the criteria of the DOH for the health centers with birthing facility to be able to utilize the 2nd floor of the building for its intended purpose; and

Immediately conduct inspection of the donated items upon delivery of the same; and

The CAD to record all donations, whether in cash or in kind, in the books of accounts of the City.

The City Social Welfare and Development Office (CSWDO): 

Conduct regular project visit and proper monitoring, and exert effort to collect the amount that should be collected to date. Conduct a meeting for those members who failed to pay their weekly amortization and know the reasons for the delays of such payments;

Regularly coordinate with the president or treasurer of the association to know the progress status of the SEA-K Program;

Set up an internal control mechanism to protect any unnecessary withdrawal of funds from the banks such as, inclusion of a CSWDO personnel as one of the signatories in the bank account and changing the combination of the signatures in the check in case of withdrawal, either the signatures of CSWDO Staff in charge and the president of the association or the CSWDO Staff in charge and the treasurer of the association; 

Require the treasurer of the association to deposit immediately the amount collected to prevent misappropriation of the same;

Conduct case study to validate the claims of those beneficiaries who had closed their microenterprises and provide additional guidelines in case of false claims;

Submit project evaluation to the DSWD-NCR not only on the association as a whole but also on each individual member to easily determine and facilitate the needs of the beneficiaries; 

Conduct thorough screening for the next beneficiaries of the program; and

Perform other duties necessary for the success of the program.

The City Budget Office/CTD  to see to it that estimated revenues are reasonably projected as collectible for the ensuing year so that projects are appropriately planned;

The CED to ensure that the projects are implemented fully as planned and within the timeframe; and

The City Planning and Development Office to come up with projects with developmental impact that would improve the socio-economic condition of the locality.

The GAD Focal Point System to:

Develop and implement more GAD related PPAs that advocate women empowerment, promote gender equality and improve the welfare of women that will protect and fulfill their rights;

Institute effective measures to monitor and report on the implementation of GAD PPAs to ensure that the different concerns of women and men are addressed equally and equitably in their PAPs in accordance with the above provisions of PCW/DILG/ DBM/NEDA; and

Adhere to the PCW, NEDA and DBM Joint Circular No. 2012-01 in the Preparation of Annual GAD Plan and Budget, and Accomplishment Report; and to COA Circular No. 2014-001 for the timely submission of the said reports to the COA Audit Team;

The City Planning and Development Office, in coordination with the GAD Focal Point System to establish a GAD database with complete information to ensure the generation, processing, review, and updating of sex-disaggregated data that will serve as basis in performance-based and gender-responsive planning and budgeting; and

The CTD to ensure that estimated revenues are reasonably projected as collectible for the ensuing year so that PAPs are appropriately planned.

